According to this article dated March 2019 which is towards the end of timeseries we are working with, Rapido was operational in about 25 cities. https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/bike-taxi-service-rapido-to-double-its-presence-to-50-cities-in-6-months/article26546085.ece. The reason why this is helpful is because it helps us create clusters from the latitude and longitude data. Ride requests definitely seem to be higher in Bangalore than in other cities and towns.

Now, the right way to cluster geographical coordinates would be to use DBSCAN with haversine distance - DBSCAN is a density based spatial clustering algorithm that clusters points that are closely packed together, haversine distance is just the spherical distance between 2 points. This is something that this paper (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1803.08101.pdf) talks about. This approach helps form clusters that have low intra-geodetic distance, which is what we want. However, the algorithm is computationally very expensive and an alternative would be to use K-Means algorithm. The problem with K-Means is that it tends to form clusters that roughly have an equal number of observations. In our dataset where there are a lot of ride requests from Bangalore, this approach would result in forming more clusters in Bangalore that are not very meaningful. Thus the number of clusters cannot be high. The number of clusters also cannot be low because we would like to cover as many cities as possible. In this case there is also a chance that Mysore and Bangalore get clustered together.

A neat way to check if the clusters are meaningful would be to compute the haversine distance between cluster centres and within clusters and see if it makes sense

In [18]:
# After some elementary hyperparameter tuning, I have settled down on a k of 20
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=20, init='k-means++', random_state=0, n_jobs=-1)
kmeans.fit(df_taxi[['pick_lat','pick_lng']])
df_taxi['minor_cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

The cluster centres seem to be distributed in a similar fashion to the scatterplot of pick up coordinates. In that sense, the clusters look sensible

In [20]:
# A useful function picked up from https://www.kaggle.com/gunbl4d3/xgboost-ing-taxi-fares
def sphere_dist(coord1, coord2):
    """
    Return distance along great radius between two coordinates.
    """
    lat1, lon1 = coord1[0], coord1[1]
    lat2, lon2 = coord2[0], coord2[1]
    #Define earth radius (km)
    R_earth = 6371
    #Convert degrees to radians
    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(np.radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])
    #Compute distances along lat, lon dimensions
    dlat = lat1 - lat2
    dlon = lon1 - lon2
    
    #Compute haversine distance
    a = np.sin(dlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2.0)**2
    
    return 2 * R_earth * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))

This makes sense as we can see that the cluster centres are meaningfully apart from each other.

From the above plots, we can see that the factors that matter the most with respect to count of ride requests are geography and hour of the day. Thus our aggregation has to be done at an hourly level. There could however be gaps in the timeseries. The problem is the data given to us only contains timestamps when ride requests were placed. It obviously does not contain, timestamps when there was no demand. If we are predicting demand for the future, we would very much like to know demand for all clusters at all hours on all days. Otherwise our model will be very biased and will always predict that there is demand.

# Formatting datetime is expensive. We can instead create a smaller dataframe of dates in a year and merge it 
# to the original
date_vars = ['Day','Month','Year']
df_model_data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_model_data.rename(columns={'day':'Day','month':'Month','year':'Year'})[date_vars])
df_date = df_model_data[['date']]
df_date = df_date.drop_duplicates()
df_date['day_num'] = [i for i in range(1,df_date.shape[0]+1)]
df_model_data = pd.merge(df_model_data, df_date, how='left', on='date')

# Some useful features
df_model_data['is_weekend'] = df_model_data['dayofweek'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x in [5,6] else 0)
df_model_data['week_num'] = (df_model_data['day_num']/7).astype(int)+1
df_model_data.drop(['day','year','month','date'], axis=1, inplace=True)
In [24]:
grid = [] 
grid_cols = ['minor_cluster', 'hour', 'day_num']
for day_num in df_model_data['day_num'].unique():
    cur_clusters = df_model_data.loc[df_model_data['day_num'] == day_num, 'minor_cluster'].unique()
    cur_hours = np.arange(0,24)
    grid.append(np.array(list(product(*[cur_clusters, cur_hours, [day_num]])),dtype='int32'))
df_grid = pd.DataFrame(np.vstack(grid), columns = grid_cols, dtype=np.int32)
del grid
df_grid = pd.merge(df_grid, df_model_data[grid_cols + ['count']], on=grid_cols, how='left')
# To add in other df_model_data attributes such as is_weekend etc.
df_grid = pd.merge(df_grid, df_model_data[['day_num','dayofweek','is_weekend','week_num']].drop_duplicates(),
                   on=['day_num'], how='left')
# Lags produce null values when there is no demand
df_grid['count'] = df_grid['count'].fillna(0)
# Another useful feature
df_grid['is_midnight'] = df_grid['hour'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x in range(0,8) else 0)

def map_clusters(cluster_id):
    if cluster_id in [0,10,16]:
        return(1)
    elif cluster_id in [2,4]:
        return(2)
    else:
        return(3)
    
df_grid['major_cluster'] = df_grid['minor_cluster'].map(map_clusters)

# Calculating mean encodings (groupby of count on multiple features)
df_grid['minclust_enc'] = df_grid.groupby(['day_num','minor_cluster','hour'])['count'].transform('mean') # Not required 
df_grid['majclust_enc'] = df_grid.groupby(['day_num','major_cluster','hour'])['count'].transform('mean')

# Lagging the encodings and deleting them since we will not know the encodings for the future observations
def lag_feature(df, lags, col):
    tmp = df[['day_num','minor_cluster','hour',col]]
    for i in lags:
        shifted = tmp.copy()
        shifted.columns = ['day_num','minor_cluster','hour', col+'_lag_'+str(i)]
        shifted['day_num'] += i
        df = pd.merge(df, shifted, on=['day_num','minor_cluster','hour'], how='left')
    df.drop(col, axis=1, inplace=True)
    return(df)

for col in ['minclust_enc', 'majclust_enc']:
    df_grid = lag_feature(df_grid, [7,14], col)
df_grid = df_grid[df_grid['day_num']>=15]
df_grid['diff_lag'] = df_grid['majclust_enc_lag_7'] - df_grid['majclust_enc_lag_14']
df_grid.fillna(0, inplace=True)

Modelling¶

The data at an hour level is too noisy to forecast. If the output of the demand prediction model were to be used as an input to a resource allocation/optimization model, we would want to account for the number of ride requests that could get placed a week from now. This would give sufficient time to hire riders and work on the technical infrastructure to handle requests, if necessary. We have seen from the plots above that the count of ride requests at a day level seem to "repeat" on a periodic basis (every 7 days). In order to work with as much data as possible, we will forecast at a minor_cluster and hour level and aggregate them to calculate the number of ride requests that could get placed on a given day.

The spikes in ride requests are not outliers. They need to be accounted for. However, for major cluster 3, there are a lot of zeros as the demand at certain hours for a lot of clusters is zero. If we were to use a single model for predicting demand for all clusters, the spikes and zeros could wreak havoc and result in poor forecasts. We will thus use 3 seperate models to predict for the 3 major clusters.

In order to account for the spikes, we will use MSE (Mean Squared Error) as the loss to minimize. MAE (Mean Absolute Error) usually favors smaller values. To calculate the difference ride requests and predictions, aggregated at a day level, MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error) will be used

linreg_cols = list(set(df_grid.columns) - set(['day_num','count','major_cluster','minor_cluster','dayofweek']))
In [71]:
def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred): 
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

def plot_coef(coef, predictors):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    coef = pd.Series(coef, predictors).sort_values()
    coef.plot(kind='bar', title='Model Coefficients')
    
def plot_features(booster, figsize):    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=figsize)
    return plot_importance(booster=booster, ax=ax)

def calculate_mape_day(pred, valid, display_minclust_mape=False):
    df_valid = valid.copy()
    df_valid['pred'] = pred
    
    df_valid_grouped = df_valid.groupby(['minor_cluster','day_num']).agg(sum_count=('count',np.sum), sum_pred=('pred',np.sum))
    df_valid_grouped['mape_day'] = df_valid_grouped.apply(lambda group: mean_absolute_percentage_error(group['sum_count'], group['sum_pred']), axis=1)
    mape_day = df_valid_grouped['mape_day'].mean()
    print('The MAPE on a day level for the major cluster is', mape_day)
    if display_minclust_mape:
        display(df_valid_grouped)
    return(mape_day)

I have used a combination of Linear Regression and XGBoost to predict ride requests. The linear trend in the data calls for the use of a linear model and I have used a tree based model so as to work with categorical variables without one-hot encoding them and to reduce the variance of forecasts. This was somewhat inspired by the results I could achieve here - https://www.kaggle.com/akshayt19nayak/classification-vs-regression-gbdt-and-ensembling/notebook

In order to validate the forecasts, I have used nested time-series validation. This has been described here (https://towardsdatascience.com/time-series-nested-cross-validation-76adba623eb9). We consider all data until the 48th week to predict for the 49th week, then use all data until the 49th week to predict for the 50th week and so on. K-Fold cross validation cannot be used due to the temporal nature of the data

In [72]:
def validate(linreg, xgboost, linreg_cols, xgboost_cols, df_train, cluster,
                         days_between=[(338,344),(345,352),(353,359),(360,366)]):
    
    # Subset major cluster
    df_train_cluster = df_train[(df_train['major_cluster']==cluster)]
    
    # Train and predict
    list_mape_day = []
    for days in days_between:
        start_date = days[0]
        end_date = days[1]
        train = df_train_cluster[(df_train_cluster['day_num']<start_date)]
        valid = df_train_cluster[(df_train_cluster['day_num']>=start_date)&(df_train_cluster['day_num']<=end_date)]
        
        # linear regression 
        linreg.fit(train[linreg_cols], train['count'])
        linreg_pred = linreg.predict(valid[linreg_cols])
        
        # xgboost
        xgboost.fit(train[xgboost_cols], train['count'], eval_metric="rmse", early_stopping_rounds=10, verbose=0,
                    eval_set=[(train[xgboost_cols], train['count']),(valid[xgboost_cols], valid['count'])])
        xgboost_pred = xgboost.predict(valid[xgboost_cols])
                
        # Combining prediction
        pred = (linreg_pred + xgboost_pred)/2
        list_mape_day.append(calculate_mape_day(pred, valid))
        
    print('The average MAPE on all folds is', np.mean(list_mape_day))
    return(linreg, xgboost)
